# Cloud Computing Lab - Program 6
## Program 6: Run PHP Code on EC2 Instance That Retrieves Data from RDS Server

Step-by-Step Execution
Step 1: Verify RDS Database from Program 5

Since the RDS database was already created in Program 5, first verify that it is running.

Go to:

AWS Console → RDS → Databases

Open:

pg05-mysql-db

Check that status is:

Available

Copy the RDS endpoint.

It will look like:

pg05-mysql-db.xxxxxxxxxxxx.ap-south-1.rds.amazonaws.com

Also note:

Port: 3306
Username: admin
Password: Admin12345
Database: cloud_lab
Table: students
Step 2: Verify RDS Security Group

For EC2 to connect to RDS, the RDS security group must allow MySQL traffic.

Go to:

EC2 Dashboard → Security Groups → RDS-SG

Check inbound rule:

Type: MySQL/Aurora
Protocol: TCP
Port: 3306
Source: EC2 security group or 0.0.0.0/0

For lab exam, if connection fails, use:

Source: 0.0.0.0/0

This allows the EC2 instance to connect to the RDS database.

Step 3: Launch Ubuntu EC2 Instance

Go to:

EC2 Dashboard → Instances

Click:

Launch instances

Enter instance name:

PG06-PHP-EC2

Choose AMI:

Ubuntu Server

Choose instance type:

t2.micro

or:

t3.micro

Choose key pair:

cloud-lab-key

In Network settings, click:

Edit

Select:

VPC: Lab-VPC
Subnet: Public-Subnet
Auto-assign public IP: Enable

Use or create a security group with the following inbound rules:

Type: SSH
Port: 22
Source: My IP or 0.0.0.0/0
Type: HTTP
Port: 80
Source: 0.0.0.0/0

Optional:

Type: HTTPS
Port: 443
Source: 0.0.0.0/0

Click:

Launch instance

Wait until the instance state becomes:

Running

Copy the EC2 public IPv4 address.

Step 4: Connect to EC2 from Ubuntu Terminal

Open your local Ubuntu terminal.

Go to the folder where the key pair is stored:

cd ~/Downloads

Give permission to the key file:

chmod 400 cloud-lab-key.pem

Connect to EC2:

ssh -i cloud-lab-key.pem ubuntu@EC2-PUBLIC-IP

Example:

ssh -i cloud-lab-key.pem ubuntu@13.233.xx.xx

After successful login, the terminal will look like:

ubuntu@ip-10-1-1-xx:~$

This means you are now inside the Ubuntu EC2 instance.

Step 5: Install Apache, PHP, PHP-MySQL, and MySQL Client

Inside the EC2 terminal, run:

sudo apt update -y
sudo apt install -y apache2 php libapache2-mod-php php-mysql mysql-client

Restart Apache:

sudo systemctl restart apache2

Enable Apache:

sudo systemctl enable apache2

Check Apache status:

sudo systemctl status apache2

Expected status:

active (running)
Step 6: Test Apache Web Server

Open browser on your local system and enter:

http://EC2-PUBLIC-IP

Example:

http://13.233.xx.xx

If Apache is installed correctly, the default Apache page or web page should open.

Step 7: Test MySQL Connection from EC2 to RDS

Inside the EC2 terminal, connect to RDS:

mysql -h RDS-ENDPOINT -P 3306 -u admin -p

Example:

mysql -h pg05-mysql-db.xxxxxxxxxxxx.ap-south-1.rds.amazonaws.com -P 3306 -u admin -p

Enter password:

Admin12345

After successful connection, MySQL prompt appears:

mysql>

Run:

SHOW DATABASES;

Use the database:

USE cloud_lab;

Check table records:

SELECT * FROM students;

Expected output:

+----+--------+-----------------+-------+
| id | name   | course          | marks |
+----+--------+-----------------+-------+
|  1 | Musaib | Cloud Computing |    95 |
|  3 | Sara   | Database        |    88 |
+----+--------+-----------------+-------+

Exit MySQL:

EXIT;

This confirms that the EC2 instance can communicate with the RDS server.

Step 8: Go to Apache Web Root Directory Inside EC2

This step must be done inside the EC2 Ubuntu terminal, not on the local Ubuntu system.

Go to the Apache web root directory:

cd /var/www/html

Check current files:

ls

The /var/www/html folder is the Apache web server folder where PHP files must be placed.

Step 9: Create Database Connection File

Inside EC2, create a file named:

db.inc.php

Run:

sudo nano db.inc.php

Paste the following PHP code:

<?php
$servername = "RDS-ENDPOINT";
$username   = "admin";
$password   = "Admin12345";
$dbname     = "cloud_lab";

$conn = new mysqli($servername, $username, $password, $dbname);

if ($conn->connect_error) {
    die("Connection failed: " . $conn->connect_error);
}
?>

Replace:

RDS-ENDPOINT

with your actual RDS endpoint.

Example:

$servername = "pg05-mysql-db.xxxxxxxxxxxx.ap-south-1.rds.amazonaws.com";

Save the file:

Ctrl + O
Enter
Ctrl + X
Step 10: Create PHP Main Page

Inside the same directory:

cd /var/www/html

Create:

sudo nano index.php

Paste this code:

<?php
include 'db.inc.php';
?>

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>PG-06 PHP and RDS</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            margin: 30px;
        }

        h1 {
            color: #222;
        }

        table {
            border-collapse: collapse;
            width: 80%;
            margin-top: 20px;
        }

        th, td {
            border: 1px solid black;
            padding: 10px;
            text-align: left;
        }

        th {
            background-color: #f2f2f2;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<h1>PG-06: PHP Connected to RDS Successfully</h1>
<h2>Student Details from Amazon RDS</h2>

<?php
$sql = "SELECT * FROM students";
$result = $conn->query($sql);

if ($result->num_rows > 0) {
    echo "<table>";
    echo "<tr><th>ID</th><th>Name</th><th>Course</th><th>Marks</th></tr>";

    while ($row = $result->fetch_assoc()) {
        echo "<tr>";
        echo "<td>" . $row["id"] . "</td>";
        echo "<td>" . $row["name"] . "</td>";
        echo "<td>" . $row["course"] . "</td>";
        echo "<td>" . $row["marks"] . "</td>";
        echo "</tr>";
    }

    echo "</table>";
} else {
    echo "No records found";
}

$conn->close();
?>

</body>
</html>

Save the file:

Ctrl + O
Enter
Ctrl + X
Step 11: Set File Permissions

Run:

sudo chown -R www-data:www-data /var/www/html
sudo chmod -R 755 /var/www/html

Restart Apache:

sudo systemctl restart apache2
